Trim the @carrot{1}, then coarsely grate (no need to peel). Halve the @green pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Chop into 1cm chunks. Peel and grate the @garlic{3%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a large #frying pan{} on high heat (no oil). Once hot, add the pepper chunks and cook until charred, ~{5-6%minutes}. Adjust the heat if necessary. Stir only twice during this time - you want the pepper to pick up some nice colour.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a medium #saucepan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add half the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}. Add the @water{220%ml}(for the bulgur), half the @chicken stock paste{10%g} and bring to the boil.

Stir in the @bulgur wheat{110%g}, bring back up to the boil and simmer for ~{1%minute}. Pop a #lid{} on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Add the @British beef mince{240%g} and grated carrot to the charred pepper. Fry until the mince has browned and the carrot has softened, ~{5-6%minutes}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Use a #spoon{} to break it the mince as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the remaining garlic, @Cajun spice mix{1} and @tomato puree{30%ml} to the beef, (add less Cajun spice mix if you'd prefer things milder). Stir-fry for ~{30%seconds}.

Next, stir the remaining @chicken stock paste{10%g}, @sun-dried tomato paste{25%g} and @water{100%ml}(for the sauce) into the beef. Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat slightly and simmer until the sauce has thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pick the @mint{1}(leaves picked from stalks and roughly chopped) leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Stir half of the mint through the cooked bulgur.

Taste the beef and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Share the minty bulgur between your #bowls{} and top with the Cajun beef. Finish with a scattering of the remaining mint. Enjoy!